Peel and finely chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely chopped) and the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Roughly chop your @chestnut mushrooms{1%pack}(roughly chopped). Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{2}(finely chopped). Boil a #pot{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} for your broccoli.

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} over high heat. Add the mushrooms in small batches and cook until they go golden brown, then remove from the pan. Add the chopped shallot and garlic to the now empty pan and reduce the heat to medium-low. Cook for ~{3-4%minutes} until softened, if the pan gets too dry add a splash of water.

Return the mushrooms to the pan along with half the @vegetable stock pot{1/2}, 200ml of water and a few good grinds of @pepper{}. Allow to simmer over medium heat for ~{8-10%minutes} until thickened.

In another frying pan, heat @oil{2%tbsp} on medium-high heat. When hot, add the @gnocchi{300%g}. Gently fry for ~{8%minutes} until it's crispy around the edges. Remove from the heat. Meanwhile, cut the @broccoli{1}(cut into small florets) into small florets. Plunge into the #pot{} of boiling water for ~{3%minutes}, then remove, drain and keep to the side.

Stir the @creme fraiche{1/2} into the mushroom sauce. Once cooked, add the gnocchi and the broccoli to the sauce and give it all a good stir. Taste for seasoning and add more salt and pepper as you wish.

Divide the gnocchi between your #bowls{} and top with the @grated hard Italian style cheese{2} and the chopped parsley.

> Whilst researching all things aphrodisiac in the run up to Valentine's week, our Mimi discovered that most ingredients have at least some reason for making us feel frisky. Since this is a family show we won't go into the ins and outs of the mushroom's sexy reputation, suffice to say that tonight's dinner, combined with a bit of Marvin Gaye could hit all the right notes. Let's get it on.